INSERT INTO `BODYCONTENT` VALUES (163841,'Welcome to the tutorial on a page\\! This page contains all the topics from the [tutorial|Tutorial].\n\nOn this page:\n{toc}\n\nh2. Using the menus\n\n{excerpt-include:Using the menus|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Creating a space\n\n{excerpt-include:Creating a space|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Creating a page\n\n{excerpt-include:Creating a page|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Adding content to a page\n\n{excerpt-include:Adding content to a page|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Using the Dashboard\n\n{excerpt-include:Using the Dashboard|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Updating your user profile\n\n{excerpt-include:Updating your user profile|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Adding a comment to a page\n\n{excerpt-include:Adding a comment to a page|nopanel=true}\n\nh2. Creating a blog post\n\n{excerpt-include:Creating a blog post|nopanel=true}',32792),(163842,'Once you have completed the [tutorial|Tutorial] and read the [advanced topics|Advanced Topics], you may want to refer to the Confluence online documentation.\n\n\nh4. Detailed instructions on using and administering Confluence\n [Confluence User Guide|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+User%27s+Guide]\n[Confluence Administrator Guide|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+Administrator%27s+Guide]\n\\\\\n\\\\\nh4. More background on Confluence\n[Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/wiki.jsp]\n[Feature Tour|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/features/]\n[Wiki Solutions|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/solutions/]\n\\\\\n\\\\\nh4. Information for people evaluating Confluence\n[Evaluator Resources |http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONFEVAL]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{include:_Links|nopanel=true}\n\\\\\n\\\\',32785),(163843,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Have Fun] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Examples]\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=none}Confluence lets you easily embed content from popular user-generated sites like Youtube, Flickr, Slideshare, Google, Twitter and many other others.\n* *Add a YouTube video to this page* by clicking the \'edit\' button and pasting \\*{{\\{widget:url={nolink}[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIcv2V_Qwf8/]{nolink}\\}}}\\* at the bottom of the page.{tip}\n{section}\n{column}\n\nh3. Managing HR Projects with Confluence\n{widget:url=http://app.episodic.com/shows/13/episodes/l6m8em4tzacd}\n{column}\n{column:width=1%}\n{column}\n{column}\n\nh3. Effective Delivery of HR Initiatives with Confluence\n{widget:url=http://app.episodic.com/shows/13/episodes/l6mls9kftfsb}\n{column}\n{section}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Have Fun] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Examples]\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.',32774),(163844,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Team Blog] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Examples]\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=none}Confluence lets you easily embed content from popular user-generated sites like Youtube, Flickr, Slideshare, Google, Twitter and many other others.\n* *Add a YouTube video* to this page by clicking the \'edit\' button and pasting \\*{{\\{widget:url={nolink}[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oHg5SJYRHA0]{nolink}\\}}}\\* at the bottom of the page.{tip}\n{section}\n{column}\n\nh3. Confluence Overview\n\nThis video gives users a basic understanding of how Confluence works and how it can help them do their jobs.\n{widget:url=http://app.episodic.com/shows/13/episodes/ob05qze293ie}\n{column}\n{column:width=1%}\n{column}\n{column}\nh3. What\'s New in Confluence 3.1\n\nBatch upload files and embed Office documents in Confluence pages using drag-and-drop.\n{widget:url=http://app.episodic.com/shows/13/episodes/oce57tsh24h2}\n{column}\n{section}\n{section}\n{column}\nh3. Introducing Drag-and-Drop\n\nBatch upload files and embed Office documents in Confluence pages using drag-and-drop.\n{widget:url=http://app.episodic.com/shows/13/episodes/o4qiwcwlawhz}\n{column}\n{column:width=1%}\n{column}\n{column}\nh3. Wiki Adoption\n\nThis slideshow can give customers an idea of how to propagate an enterprise wiki throughout their organisation.\n{widget:url=http://www.slideshare.net/mcannonbrookes/organisational-wiki-adoption}\n{column}\n{section}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Team Blog] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Examples]\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32847),(163845,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Company Birthday List] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|How the Talent Team at Atlassian use Confluence] \n\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=none}Confluence lets you easily embed content from popular user-generated sites like Youtube, Flickr, Slideshare, Google, Twitter and many other others.\n* *Add a YouTube video to this page* by clicking the \'edit\' button and pasting *{{\\{widget:url={nolink}http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LIcv2V_Qwf8/{nolink}\\}}}* at the bottom of the page.{tip}\n\nWe work hard to create useful products that people lust after, but we also know how to have fun. So what exactly is it like to work and have fun here?\n{section}\n{column}\nh3. Life at Atlassian\n\nWe\'ve created a culture of openness and honesty, with no bullshit and no bureaucracy. Learn all about our values in the video below:\n\n{widget:url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EtEgMc1bQTs}\n{column}\n{column:width=1%}\n{column}\n{column}\nh3. San Francisco Holiday Party - December 2007\n\nThe San Francisco crew chose for their holiday event a night of great food and jazz at the newly opened Yoshi\'s on Fillmore in San Francisco.\n\n{widget:url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RYeYutnFfNU}\n{column}\n{section}\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Company Birthday List] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|How the Talent Team at Atlassian use Confluence] \n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32838),(163846,'{section}\n{column:width=600px}\n\nh3. Welcome to Confluence\n----\n!_Images^img_welcome.png|width=590,height=279!\n{column}\n{column:width=300px}\n\nh3. Examples and Tutorials\n----\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_examples.png!|Examples]\\\\\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_tutorial.png!|Tutorial]\\\\\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_advanced.png!|Advanced topics]\\\\\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_plugins.png!|Featured Plugins]\n\n{column}\n{column}\n{column}\n{section}',32802),(163847,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nThe image below gives an overview of the menus in Confluence. The menus give you access to all the available actions on your Confluence site.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n!_images^MenuOverview.png!\n\\\\\n\\\\\n|| Menu or option || Explanation ||\n| *Browse* menu |The \'Browse\' menu gives access to wiki content such as pages, blog posts, etc, and allows you to browse the People Directory. If you are an administrator, the space and site administration options appear here too. |\n| *User* menu | After you have logged in, your name will appear at top right of the screen. The \'User\' menu appears when your cursor hovers over your name. The menu allows you to log out, access your user profile, editing history, personal labels, page watches and the activities of other users in your network. You can also retrieve drafts of pages you are editing. |\n|*Search* box | Type into this box and press \'Enter\' to search. |\n| *Edit* button | The \'Edit\' button allows you to edit the page. |\n| *Add* menu | The \'Add\' menu allows you to add things to a page or space.|\n| *Tools* menu | The \'Tools\' menu contains miscellaneous actions relating to the page.|\n| *Labels* | This line shows labels (or tags) attached to the current page. |\n{column}\n\n\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nIf your Confluence administrator has customised your Confluence site, then the menus may appear in different positions from those shown here.\n\nIf you are not logged in to Confluence,  the \'Browse\' menu and the \'User\' menu will not appear. Instead, a \'Log In\' link will appear.\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}\n{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Home]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Creating a space]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32803),(163848,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow you will change your Confluence \'Full Name\' (that is, the name  by which you are known to other Confluence users) and profile picture (that is, the picture by which you are known to other Confluence users).\n# Log in to Confluence, if you are not logged in already, by clicking the \'*Log In*\' link at the top right of your Confluence screen.\n!_Images^LoginLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# From the menu under your name, select \'*Profile*\'.\n!_Images^UserPreferencesMenu.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# The \'*Profile*\' view of your user profile appears.\n!_Images^UserProfileView.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Edit*\' link within the \'*Personal*\' section on the right-hand-side of this view.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# In the \'*Full Name*\' box, correct the spelling or type an alternative version of your name (e.g. a nickname).\n!_Images^UserChangeName.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Save*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your Full Name has now been changed.\n\\\\\n\\\\  (/) Hint: Changing your Full Name does not affect your login name (i.e. username).\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Still in the \'*Profile*\' view, click \'*Picture*\' at the left of the screen.\n!_Images^UserProfilePictureLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Browse*\' button, and select a photo of yourself (e.g. a GIF, JPG or PNG file) from your computer. Then click the \'*Upload*\' button.\n!_Images^UserProfilePictureUpload.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\  (/) If you don\'t have a suitable image file, select one of the \'*Default Icons*\' instead. Here are some of them. You will find more on your Profile Picture screen.\n!_Images^UserProfilePictureDefaults.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# If the picture you selected is too big, you can now trim it. You will see your picture, with a highlighted box somewhere in the middle. Click and drag the box so that it covers the area of the picture you want. Pull the corners of the box in or out to select a larger or smaller area.\n!_Images^CropProfilePicture.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Save*\' button. Confluence will use the area of the picture which you have selected, and will resize it to the required size (48 pixels by 48 pixels).\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your profile picture will appear next to any comments that you add and next to your updates on the Dashboard. Here\'s an example:\n!_Images^UserProfilePictureExample.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nYour user profile contains your user details (e.g. your name, your picture and your password) and your Confluence user preferences (e.g. time zone and email format). For more information about updating your user profile, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/yyAC].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Using the Dashboard]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Adding a comment to a page]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32806),(163849,'*On this page:*\n{toc}\n\n{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nIn the [previous step|Creating a page], you created a page with some sample content. Now you will edit the page you have created and add some more content.\n\nh4. Opening the page for editing\n\n# If you are not already viewing the page, go to the page you want to edit.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Edit*\' button on the page you want to edit. The button looks like this:\n!_Images^EditLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click an empty line in the large \'*Rich Text*\' area, below the symbols \'*B* *{_}I{_}* *{+}U{+}*\'.\n!_Images^PageContent.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Press the \'Enter\' key twice to create two new lines.\n\nh4. Inserting an image\n\n# Click the \'*Insert Image*\' icon on your page.\n!_Images^InsertImageIcon.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# The \'Insert Image\' window will appear. Ensure that \'Attached Images\' is selected on the left of the window and click the \'*Browse*\' button.\n!_Images^InsertImageScreen.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# A popup window will appear. Select an image file from your computer or your network and click \'*OK*\' to upload it to Confluence.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your image appears in the \'Insert Image\' window. Click the image you have just attached to select it.\n!_Images^InsertImageScreen2.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Insert*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your selected image now appears on your page.\n\nFor more information about working with images, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/jhYC].\n\nh4. Inserting a link\n\n# Press the \'Enter\' key twice to create two more new lines.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Type the following sentence: \'What is a wiki?\'.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Select the word \'wiki\', then click the \'*Insert Link*\' icon on your page.\n!_Images^InsertLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# The \'Insert Link\' window will appear.\n!_Images^InsertLinkScreen.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click \'*Web Link*\' and type \'http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/wiki.jsp\' in the \'*URL*\' box.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Insert*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# The word \'wiki\' is now a link.\n!_Images^LinkedText.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n\nFor more information about working with links, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/8RUC].\n\nh4. Inserting a table\n\n# Press the \'Enter\' key twice to create two more new lines.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Insert Table*\' icon on your page.\n!_Images^InsertTableIcon.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# The \'Insert/Modify Table\' window will appear. Click the \'*OK*\' button.\n!_Images^InsertTableScreen.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# A table with four rows and three columns now appears on your page.\n!_Images^MyNewTable.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click in the column headings or other table cells to add your content to the table.\n!_Images^MyNewTable2.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n\nFor more information about working with tables, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/DxUC].\n\nh4. Saving your changes\n\n* Click the \'*Save*\' button to save your page.\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nThese instructions assume that you are using the Rich Text Editor.\n\nIf you are using Wiki Markup instead, please take a look at the documentation on [working with images|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/7CAC], [working with links|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/cCAC] and [working with tables|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/iSAC].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Creating a page]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Using the Dashboard]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32804),(163850,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow you will create a page in your new space.\n\\\\\n\\\\ (/) Hint: Perform these instructions in the new browser window which you opened previously. (See [Creating a space]).\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Under the \'*Add*\' menu, select \'*Page*\'.\n!_Images^AddPageMenu.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# A new, blank page appears.\n!_Images^NewPage.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click in the box near the top of the screen, where the words \'*New Page*\' appear. The words \'New Page\' will disappear. Type a title for your page (e.g. \'About this space\').\n!_Images^PageName.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click in the large \'*Rich Text*\' area, below the symbols \'*B* *{_}I{_}* *{+}U{+}*\'. Type a sentence or two (e.g. a description of your space).\n!_Images^PageContent.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Press the \'Enter\' key twice, to create two new lines.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Select \'*Heading 2*\' from the \'Text Styles\' box above the \'Rich Text\' area, then type \'This is a big heading\'.\n!_Images^FormatMenu.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Press the \'Enter\' key twice more to create two more new lines.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Select \'*Heading 5*\' from the \'Text Styles\' box, then type \'This is a small heading\'.\n\\\\\n\\\\ (/) Below the \'Rich Text\' area you will find the page\'s *Location*, *Restrictions* and *Labels*. You don\'t need to change anything at this time.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Save*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# You can now see your newly created page.\n!_Images^MyNewPage.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nThis tutorial introduces you to the Confluence Rich Text editor, which is similar to text editors you may have used in other software programs. Alternatively, you can choose to use Wiki Markup (a simple content-formatting language, known as Confluence Notation). A quick notation guide, *Help Tips*, appears at the right of the screen when you choose the \'*Wiki Markup*\' edit tab. You can then click the \'*Full notation guide*\' link to view the full Notation Guide. For more information about Confluence Notation, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/CyEC].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Creating a space]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Adding content to a page]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32805),(163851,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow you will create a blog post in your new space.\n\\\\\n\\\\  (/) Hint: Perform these instructions in the new browser window which you opened previously. (See [Creating a space]).\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Under the \'*Add*\' menu, select \'*Blog Post*\'.\n!_Images^AddBlogPostMenu.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# A new, blank blog post appears.\n!_Images^NewBlogPost.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click in the box near the top of the screen, where the words \'*New Blog Post*\' appears. The words \'New Blog Post\' will disappear. Type a title for your blog post (e.g. \'Latest update\').\n!_Images^NewsName.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click in the large \'*Rich Text*\' area, below the symbols \'*B* *{_}I{_}* *{+}U{+}*\'. Type several sentences.\n!_Images^BlogPostContent.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\ (/) Below the \'Rich Text\' area are the page\'s Labels and Posting Day (which defaults to today). You don\'t need to change anything at this time.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Save*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# You can now see your newly created blog post.\n!_Images^MyNewNews.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\n*What is a blog post?*\nConfluence blog posts are special pages found in the \'blog\' section of each space. They can be announcements, journal entries, status reports or any other timely information you would categorise as a blog entry or \'news\'.\n\nFor more information about working with blogs, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/rSAC].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\nCongratulations, you have finished the Tutorial\\! Next, you may like to see some [examples of wiki pages|Examples], read some of the [advanced topics|Advanced topics] or take a look at our [other documentation|More information].\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Adding a comment to a page]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32808),(163852,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow you will add a comment to the page that you previously created. (See [Creating a page].)\n# Go to your new page.\n(/) For assistance on finding the page, please see [Using the Dashboard] earlier in the tutorial.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Add Comment*\' link at the bottom of the page.\n!_Images^AddCommentLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# A \'Rich Text\' area appears at the bottom of the page.\n!_Images^CommentBox.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Type a remark about the page.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Post*\' button.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your comment now appears at the bottom of the page, together with your name, the profile picture you added previously (see [Updating your user profile]) and the time your comment was made.\n!_Images^CommentExample.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{column}\n\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nPosting comments in Confluence allows you and your colleagues to hold discussions within your wiki. You can often use the wiki instead of email, for example.\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}\n{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Updating your user profile]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Creating a blog post]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32810),(163853,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nThe following instructions will show you how to view the hierarchy of pages within a space, and move pages to different positions within the hierarchy.\n\n(/) It is suggested that you use the new space that you created during the [Tutorial] (see \'[Creating a space]\').&nbsp;\n\nPART A: First, you will create some new pages :\n# Go to the home page of your new space.\n# Under the \'*Add*\' menu, select \'*Page*\'.\n# A new, blank page appears.\n# Click in the box near the top of the screen, where the words \'*New Page*\' appear. The words \'*New Page*\' will disappear. Type the following title: \'Book One\'.\n# Save your new page and go back to the space\'s home page.\n# Repeat steps 2-5, but give your new page the title \'Chapter One\'.\n# Repeat steps 2-5, but give your new page the title \'Chapter Two\'.\n\nYou have now created three new pages. All three pages are children of the space\'s home page.\n\nPART B: Now you will view the pages within your space, and move some of your new pages into more logical positions:\n# From the \'*Browse*\' menu, select \'*Pages*\'.\n# A list of pages appears.\n# Click the plus-sign next to the word \'*Home*\'.\n# A list of pages (i.e. children of the space\'s home page) is displayed. Your three new pages are included in the list, i.e.\n#* \'Book One\'\n#* \'Chapter One\'\n#* \'Chapter Two\'\n# With your mouse, drag \'Chapter One\' onto \'Book One\'.\n# Click the plus-sign next to the word \'*Home*\'.\n# A plus-sign now appears next to the words \'Book One\'. Click this plus-sign.\n# \'Chapter One\' now appears indented below \'Book One\'. Your tree should now look like this:\n#* \'Book One\'\n#** \'Chapter One\'\n#* \'Chapter Two\'\n# With your mouse, drag \'Chapter Two\' onto \'Book One\'.\n# Click the plus-sign next to the word \'*Home*\'.\n# Click the plus-sign next to the words \'Chapter One\'. \'Your tree should now look like this:\n#* \'Book One\'\n#** \'Chapter One\'\n#** \'Chapter Two\'\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}In Confluence, you can organise pages into a hierarchy of parent and child pages. Pages in such a hierarchy are called a \'_page family_\' (or _\'page tree\'_). For more information about working with page families, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/fSAC]. By default, a new page is the child of the page you were viewing when you started creating the new page.\nThere are three ways to view the list of pages in a space. You can choose to view:\n- recently-added pages only\n\n- all pages, in alphabetic order\n\n- all pages, in hierarchical order (also known as a \'page tree\')\n\nIf the list of pages contains just the word \'Home\' with a plus-sign next to it, then you are looking at the hierarchical order. If not, click \'Tree\' (next to the word \'View\', above the list of pages).\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\',32814),(163854,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow that you have seen how the [menus|Using the menus] work, you are ready to start creating content in Confluence. Let\'s begin by adding a new space.\n# Log in to Confluence, if you are not logged in already, by clicking the \'*Log In*\' link at the top right of your Confluence screen.\n!_Images^LoginLink.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Right-click the \'*Dashboard*\' link at the top left of your screen and open the link in a new browser window.\n!_Images^DashboardRightClick.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\  (/) Hint: Perform the rest of these instructions in the new browser window.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your Confluence Dashboard appears in the new window. On the left of the screen is a list of spaces. (The Demonstration Space will be one of those spaces.)\n!_Images^Dashboard.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Add space*\' button, located below the welcome message.\n!_Images^AddSpace.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# The \'Create Space\' screen appears.\n!_Images^CreateSpaceScreen.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# In the \'*Enter a Space Name*\' box, type a name for your new space. You may want to use your department name (e.g. \'IT\', \'Finance\' or \'Marketing\') or a name that identifies the purpose of the space (e.g. \'Test Space\').\n!_Images^SpaceName.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# In the \'*Enter a Space Key*\' box, type a short abbreviation of the space name (e.g. \'IT\' or \'TEST\').\n!_Images^SpaceKey.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Under \'*Who can use this space*\', all the boxes are ticked. You don\'t need to change anything at this time. For information about space permissions, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Space+Permissions+Overview].\n!_Images^Permissions.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Under \'*Choose Theme*\', the \'Default Theme\' is selected. Keep the Default Theme for now. For information about themes, please see the [documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/DyEC].\n!_Images^DefaultTheme.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*OK*\' button, located at the bottom of the screen.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# The home page of your new space appears.\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\n*What is a space?*\nA space is an area within Confluence, containing your wiki pages. You can think of each space as a sub-site, or mini-site, each with its own home page. You are looking at a space right now, called the Demonstration Space.\n\n*How many spaces should I create?*\nThat depends on how you are planning to use Confluence. For example, if you are going to use Confluence for your intranet, you may want to create one space per department. If you want to use Confluence to write technical documentation, you could create one space per product.\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Using the menus]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Creating a page]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32812),(163855,'{excerpt}\n{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nNow you will use the Dashboard to navigate to the new page and the new space that you created in previous steps of this tutorial.\n# Right-click the \'*Dashboard*\' link at the top left of your screen, and open the link in a new browser window.\n!_Images^DashboardRightClick.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\  (/) Hint: Perform the rest of these instructions in the new browser window.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your Confluence Dashboard appears in the new window.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# On the right of your Dashboard, under the heading \'*Recently Updated*\', is a list of pages that have recently been added or edited. The page that you previously created will appear in this list (unless many other pages have been added or edited in the meantime).\n!_Images^DashboardRecentlyUpdated.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\  (/) If your page doesn\'t appear in the list, skip this step and go to step 6.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the name of the page that you previously created.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Your page appears.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the \'*Dashboard*\' link at the top left of the screen. Your Confluence Dashboard appears again.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# On the left of your Dashboard is a list of spaces. Next to each space\'s name is the \'space\' icon !_Images^web_16.gif!\n!_Images^Dashboard.png|border=1,bordercolor=gray!\\\\\n\\\\\n# Click the name of the space that you previously created.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n# The home page of your space appears.\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\nThe Dashboard is the home page of your Confluence wiki. The Dashboard contains a list of all the spaces within your wiki, as well as a list of recently updated content.\n\nFrom the Dashboard, you can click any space\'s name to go to the space\'s home page.\n\nTo get to the Dashboard from anywhere within your wiki, click the \'Dashboard\' link at the top left of your screen.\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}{excerpt}\n\\\\\n\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Adding content to a page]&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Updating your user profile]\\\\\n\\\\\n*In the tutorial:*\n{children:page=Tutorial}',32807),(163856,'{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nIf you have used Confluence before, you may be interested in the following advanced topics:\n\\\\\n{children:style=h5}\n\\\\\n{column}\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}If you are new to Confluence, you may like to start with the [Tutorial].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}\n\n{include:_Links|nopanel=true}\n\\\\\n\\\\',32811),(163857,'[!_Images^balloons_icon.png!|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+User%27s+Guide] [User Guide|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+User%27s+Guide] \\| [!_Images^cake_icon.png!|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+Administrator%27s+Guide] [Administrator Guide|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+Administrator%27s+Guide] \\| [!_Images^information_icon.png!|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/wiki.jsp] [FAQ|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/-QG6D] \\| [!_Images^wand_icon.png!|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/features/] [Feature Tour|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/features/] \\| [!_Images^book_icon.png!|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONFEVAL/] [Evaluator Resources|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/_gG6D]',32795),(163858,'The [tutorial|Tutorial] is designed primarily for evaluators who have recently downloaded and installed Confluence.\n\nIf you have already deployed Confluence in your organisation, and are using the tutorial to provide a general introduction for new users on your wiki, please note that the tutorial assumes the following to be true:\n* Your Confluence site is using the Default theme.\n* The user has the \'Create Space\' permission.\n* The user has online web access. This is recommended but not essential, because the tutorial includes links to the Confluence online documentation to provide extra information.',32856),(163859,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Meeting Notes] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Team Blog]\n\\\\\n\\\\ \n{tip:icon=none}The sales team uses charts to create a sales dashboard showing their performance relative to plan. Once you become an advanced user, you can [connect the charts to your sales database using SQL|http://blogs.atlassian.com/news/2009/08/confluence_business_intelligence_part1.html] so that you can display your sales data in real time. \n* *[Edit|Using the menus] this page and change a number in one of the charts below.* Notice how the chart changes when you preview or save your change.\n* *[Edit|Using the menus] this page and change a bar chart below into a line chart.* Change \"_type=bar_\" to \"_type=line_\" inside the \\{chart} macro. Watch the chart type change when you preview or save your change.{tip}\n{section}\n{column}\n{chart:type=bar|title=Monthly Sales|dataOrientation=vertical|rangeAxisLowerBound=500|width=500|xLabel=Month|yLabel=US$ in 000\'s|colors=,#CCCCCC|rangeaxislowerbound=500}\n|| Month || Sales ||\n| 1 | 665 |\n| 2 | 715 |\n| 3 | 750 |\n| 4 | 785 |\n| 5 | 820 |\n| 6 | 850 |\n| 7 | 890 |\n| 8 | 925 |\n| 9 | 960 |\n\n|| Month || Goal ||\n| 9 | 900 |\n| 10 | 930 |\n| 11 | 960 |\n| 12 | 990 |\n{chart}\n{column}\n{column:width=10%}\n{column}\n{column}\n{chart:type=line|title=YTD Sales|dataOrientation=vertical|rangeAxisLowerBound=500|rangeAxisUpperBound=11000|xLabel=Month|yLabel=US$ in 000\'s|width=500|colors=#6495ED,#CCCCCC|showShapes=false}\n|| Month || YTD Sales ||\n| 1 | 665 |\n| 2 | 1380 |\n| 3 | 2133 |\n| 4 | 2917 |\n| 5 | 3735 |\n| 6 | 4587 |\n| 7 | 5475 |\n| 8 | 6400 |\n| 9 | 7400 |\n\n|| Month || YTD Goal ||\n| 9 | 7,100 |\n| 10 | 8,100 |\n| 11 | 9,000 |\n| 12 | 10,000 |\n{chart}\n{column}\n{section}\n\\\\\n{excerpt}{chart:type=pie|3D=true|title=Sales by Rep|dataOrientation=vertical|width=500|colors=#6495ED,#CCCCCC|pieSectionLabel=%0% ( $%1% )|legend=false|}\n|| Pre-Sales Rep || YTD ||\n|Boots |2062|\n|Kevin |1694|\n|Matt |1694|\n|Dave |1620|\n{chart}{excerpt}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Meeting Notes] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Team Blog]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32824),(163860,'{section}\n{column:width=60%}\nThis tutorial will help you get started with Confluence:\n{children:style=h5}\n\\\\\n\\\\\n[!_Images^btn_next.png!|Using the menus]\n{column}\n\n{column}\n{info:icon=false}\n*What is a space?*\nA space is an area within Confluence, containing your wiki pages. You can think of each space as a sub-site, or mini-site, each with its own home page.\n\n*What is the Dashboard?*\nThe Dashboard is the home page of your Confluence wiki. The Dashboard contains a list of all the spaces within your wiki, as well as a list of recently updated content.\n\n*What is a wiki?*\nA wiki is a piece of software that allows you and your colleagues to create and edit web pages quickly and simply. Just click, edit and save. Content is published immediately.\n\n*What is Confluence?*\nConfluence is an enterprise wiki with some extra communication tools, including blog posts and RSS feeds.\n\n*What makes Confluence an enterprise wiki?*\nDifferent organisations use Confluence for different purposes: as a company intranet, corporate website, project workspace, knowledge base, documentation site and a host of other implementations. All these are made possible by Confluence\'s enterprise-appropriate features, including: security permissions at the page, space and site level; content structuring and restructuring options; LDAP compatibility and more.\n\n(/) If you prefer, you can see the whole tutorial [on one page|Tutorial (all on one page)].\n{info}\n{column}\n{section}',32820),(163861,'{note:title=Installing Plugins}\n\nThe plugins featured on this page are not installed out-of-the-box. To install them, please refer to our documentation on +[installing plugins|http://confluence.atlassian.com/x/loBQ]+.\n\n{note}',32855),(163862,'{section}\n{column:width=1px}\n{panel}\n{gallery:columns=2}\n{panel}\n{column}\n{column}\nThe +[Gliffy plugin|https://plugins.atlassian.com/plugin/details/254]+ allows you to easily create professional-quality flowcharts and diagrams, right in your Confluence pages.\n\nAt Atlassian, our Human Resources department used this tool to map out our recruitment process. This diagram is embedded in a Confluence page in the team\'s space where employees involved in the recruitment process can quickly understand what the next step is. For example, what step comes after the initial interview, and who is responsible for that step.\n\nh5. How to add a Diagram to a Confluence page\n# *Hover your cursor* over the _Add_ menu on any Confluence page\n# *Select _Gliffy Diagram_*\n# *Enter a name* for your diagram\n# *Use the Gliffy Web-based editor* to complete your diagram\n# Once you\'ve completed your diagram, *select _Save and Close_ from the _File_ menu in the top-left of the Gliffy editor*\n\nh5. Watch the video\n{widget:url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j-RXVsvH_m8}\n{column}\n{section} ',32854),(163863,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Atlassian Logos][!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Examples] \n{tip:icon=none}The Design Team uses Confluence to to make company standard templates available to employees. Rather than storing these files on a network shared drive, they have instead attached them to a Confluence page so that they are accessible to everyone who has the permission to view the page. Gone are the days of trying to find files on a shared drive. Confluence makes your files easily accessible, secure and searchable. Why not try:\n* *Searching for* _Happy Users_ using the search box in the top right of the screen. As Confluence has indexed the full content of the PowerPoint Presentation you will see the file in your search results which you can quickly preview by clicking *{_}View{_}*. ([_View Video Tutorial_|http://tr.im/zs6z])\n* *Attach* your own PowerPoint, Word, Excel or PDF document and *embed* it in the page using the View File Macro. ([_View Video Tutorial_|http://tr.im/zs6s])\n{tip}\n{section}\n{column:width=5%}\n{column}\n{column:width=45%}\n\nh3. Background Images\n\n\\\\\n\nh6. Content Slide\n{gallery:include=AT PPT ContentPage.png}\n[_Download_|^AT PPT ContentPage.png]\\\\\n\\\\\n\\\\\n\nh6. Title Slide\n{gallery:include=AT PPT TitlePage.png}\n[_Download_|^AT PPT TitlePage.png]\n\n{column}\n{column:width=1%}\n{column}\n{column:width=45%}\n\nh3. PowerPoint Example\n{viewppt:name=Managing_HR_Projects.pptx}\n{column}\n{column:width=5%}\n{column}\n{section}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Atlassian Logos]\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.\n{warning}',32801),(163864,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Example Human Resources Page] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|HR Policies and Procedures] \n\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=false}The Human Resources team uses [tasklists|Creating a task list] to assign and prioritise simple tasks for new employees.\n* *Add a new task to this list*\n* *Change the priority of one of the existing tasks.*{tip}\n\\\\\nWelcome, we\'re glad to have you here :-) . To help you get started, we\'ve created this simple task list of things you should accomplish in your first week. Feel free to contact anyone in HR or your buddy with any question you might have.\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{tasklist:New Employee Task List}\n||Completed||Priority||Locked||CreatedDate||CompletedDate||Assignee||Name||\n|F|H|F|          |          |barconati|Add your birthday to the birthday calendar|\n|F|H|F|          |          | |Browse the Human Resources Space and read through policies|\n|F|H|F|          |          | |Create a personal space in Confluence|\n|F|M|F|          |          | |Read the guidelines for internal blogging|\n|F|H|F|          |          | |Write an introductory blog post|\n|F|M|F|          |          | |Subscribe to the personal blog RSS feed|\n|F|M|F|1224009699780|          |barconati|Read about our products: [JIRA\\|http://www.atlassian.com/jira] [Confluence\\|http://www.atlassian.com/confluence] [Crowd\\|http://www.atlassian.com/crowd] [Bamboo\\|http://www.atlassian.com/bamboo] [FishEye\\|http://www.atlassian.com/software/fisheye] [Crucible\\|http://www.atlassian.com/software/crucible] [Clover\\|http://www.atlassian.com/software/clover]|\n|F|L|F|1224009793414|          |barconati|Sign up for the next [Confluence Webinar\\|http://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/webinar.jsp]|\n|F|L|F|1224009770051|          |barconati|Sign up for the next [JIRA Webinar\\|http://www.atlassian.com/software/jira/webinar.jsp]|\n{tasklist}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Example Human Resources Page] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|HR Policies and Procedures]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32836),(163865,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Recruitment] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Company Birthday List]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=none}Use the rich text editor to author and format documents like this overview of the Buddy System. Once the document is complete and ready to publish, simply export the document to PDF for presentation as an \'official\' document.\n* *Export this page to PDF* from the _Tools_ menu and save it to your hard drive.{tip}\n\nMost new employees begin their first day of work full of excitement and enthusiasm. Depending on first impressions, this initial enthusiasm for the organisation can be either extended and nurtured or destroyed. Everything that happens in the first few days will affect the new hire\'s perception of the organisation and the colleagues he or she will be working with.\n\nh3. Why the Buddy System\n\nA buddy system builds a personal connection between the organisation and the new employee from the first day. The new employee is made to feel part of the organisation, gains more confidence and, as a result, becomes productive more quickly. We encourage new employees to have a buddy who is outside of their own department to ensure that new employees have an understanding of what other employees do and get to know other colleagues outside of their own work group. Here\'s what some employees have to say about the buddy system:\n{quote}I\'m usually shy about meeting new people. The buddy system got me talking to people I otherwise probably wouldn\'t meet.{quote}\n{quote}After working here three years, I still go to lunch with my buddy at least once a month\\!{quote}\n{quote}My buddy made my first days at the company a lot less confusing and a lot more enjoyable.{quote}\n\nh3. Who is a Buddy?\n\nAt a minimum, the buddy should:\n# Take new employees to lunch in their first few days of employment\n# Provide an opportunity for new employees to ask questions without feeling intimidated\n# Ensure open lines of communication with new employees while respecting confidentiality\n# Offer encouragement\n# Check with the new employee every so often to answer questions and offer support (particularly in the first month of the new employee starting)\n\nh3. A Buddy is Not...\n\nThe buddy system does not replace the supervisor\'s responsibilities regarding department orientation or on-the-job training. It is not the responsibility of the buddy to train the new employee. The buddy should direct the new employee to the supervisor if the questions become more complex or involve the work itself. Also, the buddy is not responsible for the new employee\'s performance. The buddy is only there to help the new employee become socialised to the organisation.\n\nh3. So how does it work?\n\nI have set up a wiki page for this buddy system, it will have the names of all current new employees and buddies. Prior to an employee commencing, I\'ll work with the hiring manager to choose a buddy and let you know if you are the buddy for our next new hire. So if your name is there, then you are the nominated one\\!\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Recruitment] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Company Birthday List]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Warning: Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32837),(163866,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|HR Policies and Procedures]  [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Buddy System]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{tip:icon=false}Images and charts can sometimes communicate complex concepts better than text. For example, your HR team might use images to explain the company recruiting processes.\n* *Add a* *[comment|Adding a comment to a page]* *to this page* to let people what you think of the recruiting process.{tip}\n\\\\\nThis page is designed for all employees involved in recruiting, selecting or inducting new high quality people. It integrates best practice elements from several sources to help us continue to grow, globally\\!\n\n{section}\n{column:width=40%}\n\\\\\n\nh3. The Recruiting Process\n\n# Request New Staff\n# Approval\n# HR commences job advertisement\n# Pre-sreening candidates\n# Initial application review by talent\n# Assign screened candidates to interviewers\n{column}\n{column:width=60%}\n!recruiting_process.jpg|height=300px!\n{column}\n{section}\n{section}\n{column:width=40%}\n\\\\\n\nh3. The Selection Process\n\n# Application review by hiring team\n# Phone interview\n# Work history check\n# F2F Interview(s): technical skills and competencies\n# Reference checks\n# Offer\n{column}\n{column:width=60%}\n!selection_process.jpg|height=250px!\n{column}\n{section}\n[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|HR Policies and Procedures]  [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Buddy System]\n\\\\\n\\\\\n{warning:title=Sample Content}This is sample content that comes included with Confluence for the purposes of demonstrating how the product can be used.{warning}',32832),(163867,'[!_Images^btn_previous.png!|Atlassian Colours] [!_Images^btn_next.png|align=right!|Atlassian Logos]\n{tip:icon=false}Confluence is a great tool for sharing images with your staff, customers or anyone on the internet. Below is a gallery of all the Atlassian Shirts that the Design Team have created. You could use Confluence to share pictures from a company event, mockups of interfaces for new features or even screenshots of your product for use in documentation. Why not try:\n* *Clicking* on one of the shirts below to view the full-size image.\n* *Attaching* other images to this page to preview them in the gallery below. Just go 